  filter(Species == "ABCO" & !df$Fire %in% c("PLKN","FRDS"))

Change species and Sdlg to factor

df <- df %>% 
  mutate(Species = as.factor(Species)) %>% 
  mutate(Sdlg = as.factor(Sdlg))

Convert shrub area to square root

df <- df %>% 
  mutate(sqrt_shrubarea3 = sqrt(shrubarea3))

Take out rows with Inf log(VertGrowth) because growth = 0 cm

df <- df %>% 
  filter(is.finite(df$VertGrowth_Rel))

Normalize the numeric ones

normalize <- function(x) {
    return ((x - mean(x)) / sd(x))
  }
xdf <- xdf %>% mutate_if(is.numeric, normalize)

Apply VSURF to vertical growth

vsurf <- VSURF(x = xdf,
               y = df$VertGrowth_Rel,
               na.action = na.omit,
               parallel = T)

Look at a linear model using the variables that were identified by VSURF, plus interactions that seem biologically meaningful

Structure data for LM

LMdf <- df %>% 
  mutate(sqrt_shrubarea3 = sqrt(shrubarea3)) %>%
  mutate(log_shrubarea3 = log(shrubarea3)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(Fire, Sdlg, heatload, Years, BasDia2016.cm, shrubarea3, sqrt_shrubarea3, log_shrubarea3, Elevation, Ht_cm1, Slope.Deg, Year, Aspect.rad.fold.NESW, incidrad) %>% 
  mutate_if(is.numeric, normalize) %>% 
  mutate(VertGrowth_Rel = df$VertGrowth_Rel)
LMdf <- droplevels(LMdf)

See whether model with or without interaction is better

without <- lme(VertGrowth_Rel ~ 
           Ht_cm1 + heatload +  Years + Aspect.rad.fold.NESW + incidrad + BasDia2016.cm + sqrt_shrubarea3,
        data = LMdf, random = ~ 1| Fire/Sdlg, method = "ML")

with <- lme(VertGrowth_Rel ~  
           sqrt_shrubarea3*Ht_cm1 + heatload +  Years + Aspect.rad.fold.NESW + incidrad + BasDia2016.cm,
        data = LMdf, random = ~ 1| Fire/Sdlg, method = "ML")

AIC(with)
## [1] 626.4395
AIC(without)
## [1] 624.6732
anova(with, without)
##         Model df      AIC      BIC    logLik   Test   L.Ratio p-value
## with        1 12 626.4395 671.9556 -301.2197                         
## without     2 11 624.6732 666.3964 -301.3366 1 vs 2 0.2337835  0.6287

No difference, so I’ll leave out the interaction

Re-establish best model

LM <-  lme(VertGrowth_Rel ~ 
            Ht_cm1 + heatload +  Years + Aspect.rad.fold.NESW + incidrad + BasDia2016.cm + sqrt_shrubarea3,
           data = LMdf, random = ~ 1| Fire/Sdlg, method = "ML")

Check collinearity - use vif from car pkg because in pines it was the same as the Zuur code

vif(LM)
##               Ht_cm1             heatload                Years 
##             5.309572            11.464765             4.347682 
## Aspect.rad.fold.NESW             incidrad        BasDia2016.cm 
##             5.403962             2.498694             5.041820 
##      sqrt_shrubarea3 
##             1.246510

A VIF cutoff value of 5 is often used, and heatload has a GVIF off 11.8, so take it out and run the model again:

LM <-  lme(VertGrowth_Rel ~ 
          Ht_cm1 + Years + Aspect.rad.fold.NESW + incidrad + BasDia2016.cm + sqrt_shrubarea3,
           data = LMdf, random = ~ 1| Fire/Sdlg, method = "ML")

Look at individual effects

Note: the plots look exactly the same but with different axes if you don’t normalize the numeric predictors. So for including plots to visualize in the paper, I just use non-normalized data

eff_years <- predictorEffect("Years", LM)
plot(eff_years)

eff_shrubarea <- predictorEffect("sqrt_shrubarea3", LM)
plot(eff_shrubarea)

effects_df <- effects_df %>%

Find the shrubarea values associated with each quartile, and the mean growth for each of those

summary <- summary(sqrt(df$shrubarea3))
summary
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   94.39  219.06  262.63  265.27  297.54  441.56
quart1 <- summary[2]
quart3 <- summary[5]
median <- summary[3]
min <- summary[1]
max <- summary[6]
mean <- mean(sqrt(df$shrubarea3))

fit_quart1 <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - quart1)),]$fit
fit_quart1
## [1] -2.180578
fit_quart3 <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - quart3)),]$fit
fit_median <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - median)),]$fit

fit_min <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - min)),]$fit
fit_max <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - max)),]$fit
fit_mean <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - mean)),]$fit

print(paste("fit_quart1 = ", exp(fit_quart1)))
## [1] "fit_quart1 =  0.112976254280873"
print(paste("fit_quart3 = ", exp(fit_quart3)))
## [1] "fit_quart3 =  0.117688153225972"
print(paste("fit_median = ", exp(fit_median)))
## [1] "fit_median =  0.115521467377539"
print(paste("fit_mean = ", exp(fit_mean)))
## [1] "fit_mean =  0.115521467377539"
print(paste("fit_min = ", exp(fit_min)))
## [1] "fit_min =  0.105668967414413"
print(paste("fit_max = ", exp(fit_max)))
## [1] "fit_max =  0.126786218752772"

Plot effects of shrubarea

ggplot(effects_df)+
  geom_line(aes(x = sqrt_shrubarea3, y = exp(fit)))+
  geom_ribbon(aes(x = sqrt_shrubarea3, ymin = exp(lower), ymax = exp(upper)), alpha = .5, fill = "#fdbb84")+
  theme_bw()+
  xlab(bquote(
    (sqrt(`cover (cm)`%*%`height (cm)`))            
    ))+
#  xlab(bquote((sqrt(`cover (cm)`%*%`height (cm)`)))+
  ylab("Relative growth rate")+
 # ggtitle("Fir growth in relation to shrub environment within 2 m")+
  geom_rug(data = df, aes(x = sqrt(shrubarea3), y = exp(VertGrowth_Rel)), alpha = .5, position = "jitter", sides = "b")+
  ylim(c(0.04,0.3))+
  theme(
    #panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    #panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    text = element_text(size = 11))

ggsave(file = "../../results/figures/FireFootprints/FirVertRel.png", width = 3, height = 3, dpi = 400)
